issue.body:
I'm making a basic electron app, but when I try to load ipcRenderer in my preload file, it returns without all the event listener methods, including on, once, and removeListener.
preload.js: 
```javascript
const {contextBridge ,ipcRenderer} = require('electron');
const fs = require('fs');
console.log(ipcRenderer); // returns without event listeners in Electron
contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld('k',{
    ipcRenderer:ipcRenderer,
    fs:fs,
});
```
main.js:
```javascript
const {app, BrowserWindow, Menu} = require('electron');
const url = require('url');
const path = require('path');
let win;

function createWindow() {
   win = new BrowserWindow({width: 800, height: 600,webPreferences: {nodeIntegration: false,preload: path.join(__dirname, 'preload.js'),contextIsolation: true}});
   win.loadURL(url.format({
      pathname: path.join(__dirname, 'index.html'),
      protocol: 'file:',
      slashes: true
   }));
}

app.on('ready', createWindow)
```

When I load ipcRenderer in a local file with nodeIntegration enabled, it works fine, but in preload, it doesn't. 

Is this a bug with my code, and if so, what is happening, and what can I do to fix it?

Note: I'm aware that directly exposing the fs and ipcRenderer APIs is bad security policy, but I can't do anything about that until I fix this. All files are in the same directory. 

Console output in Electron app of console.log(ipcRenderer)
![Output](https://im9823.surge.sh/k.png)
This may have some relation to  #27039 or #6828 - I'm not sure whether ipcRenderer is sent across contextBridge before being logged in Electron. 

I am using Macos 11.1 for this. 

Update: the problem seems to be with contextBridge - when sent over preload normally (window.ipcRenderer = ipcRenderer), it works fine.

